Source URL: Follow the URL to glean clues for your description of an item.
dc.title: Name of the item you are describing.
dc.creator: The person or organization primarily responsible for making the item you are describing, e.g., artist, author.
dc.contributor: Person or organization responsible for making contributions to the resource, e.g. illustrator.
dc.date: Point or period of time associated with the item, e.g. date original item was created.
dc.description: A free-text account of the item you are describing.
dc.rights: Information about the rights status of the item.
dc.subject: Topic of the item you are describing.
dc.coverage: The spatial or temporal topic of the item being described: instead of the place or date when the item was created, the place or date that an item is about, e.g. the event that a monument commemorates.
dc.publisher: Person or organization responsible for making the item available.
dc.source: Citation to where this item was found, e.g. collecting institution or or print resource.
dc.format: Physical medium, file format, or dimensions of the item.
dc.type: Nature or genre of the item.
dc.identifier: An unambiguous reference to the item.

dc.title: Establish conventions, e.g. sentence case vs. title case, supplied information in brackets, etc.
dc.creator: Use a controlled vocabulary such as the Library of Congress Name Authority File (LCNAF), Union List of Artist Names (ULAN), or the Virtual International Authority File (VIAF).
dc.contributor: Use a controlled vocabulary such as the Library of Congress Name Authority File (LCNAF), Union List of Artist Names (ULAN), or the Virtual International Authority File (VIAF).
dc.date: Use the international standard for date and time formats, e.g. 2017-01-01.
dc.description: A good place for information that doesn't fit in other, more structured metadata fields.
dc.rights: Use standard descriptions such as Creative Commons licenses or the statements from RightsStatements.org.
dc.subject: Use a controlled vocabulary such as the Library of Congress Subject Headings (LCSH) or Thesaurus for Graphic Materials (TGM).
dc.coverage: For spatial topics, use a controlled vocabulary such as the Thesaurus of Geographic Names (TGN). For temporal topics, use a structured format similar to that for dc.date.
dc.publisher: Use a controlled vocabulary such as the Library of Congress Name Authority File (LCNAF), Union List of Artist Names (ULAN), or the Virtual International Authority File (VIAF).
dc.relation: Include URL to item, e.g., if it appears in another digital collection.
dc.source: Include URL to item, e.g., if it appears in another digital collection.
dc.format: Use a controlled vocabulary such as the Art & Architecture Thesaurus (AAT).
dc.type: Use a controlled vocabulary such as the DCMI Type Vocabulary.
dc.language: Use a controlled vocabulary such as RFC 5646: Tags for Identifying Languages. According to this specification English as used in the United States would en-US. Otherwise, just be consistent!
